{
  "id": "epistemic_markers",
  "analyst_summary": "Automated dictionary scorer. Counts occurrences of 106 hedge words (Hyland: 'about', 'apparent', 'argue', 'could', 'might', 'somewhat'...) and 74 booster words ('clearly', 'definitely', 'undoubtedly', 'must'...) per passage, plus per-certainty-level markers (absolute/high/moderate/low/uncertain via Rubin). Output is a profile: hedge ratio, booster ratio, certainty distribution. High hedging + low boosters = epistemic caution / face-saving. High boosters + low hedging = assertive certainty. Useful as a CoT-trace marker: shifts between reasoning and output reveal where the model commits vs. equivocates.",
  "metadata": {
    "description": "Epistemic and certainty markers for linguistic analysis",
    "sources": {
      "hedges_boosters": "Hyland, K. (2005). Metadiscourse: Exploring Interaction in Writing. Continuum. Appendix lists as reproduced in Wang & Zeng (2021), TextInspector, and multiple corpus-based studies.",
      "certainty_levels": "Rubin, V.L. (2006). Identifying Certainty in Texts. PhD diss., Syracuse University; Rubin, V.L. (2010). Epistemic modality: From uncertainty to certainty. Information Processing & Management, 46(5), 533-540; Palmer, F.R. (1986/2001). Mood and Modality. Cambridge University Press.",
      "reference_url": "https://textinspector.com/help/metadiscourse/"
    },
    "compiled": "2026-05-24"
  },
